I grew up in the south. I miss it, terribly. When I can't take it anymore, I head to Brenda's. I find it's good to go early on weekday mornings, and then you avoid the horrible hour+ wait of weekend brunch. Coffee with chicory, beignets, you're all set. But it doesn't stop there because you know you're gonna have grits. Now, at Brenda's they make the grits like my grammy used to... butter and cream. Heaven! If you aren't from the south, you may be tempted to slap some sugar on top. DO NOT DO THIS. You will not only give yourself away as a complete tourist, but also ruin what just may be the most ephemeral moment your tongue will have in San Francisco; the one where the heavy silver spoon delivers something better than your mama's milk between your anticipating lips. Uh. Got a little carried away just remembering the orgasmic moment of ecstasy savoring Brenda's.

We were visiting from NY and saw some great reviews for Brenda's, so decided to try it. The wait wasn't too bad at 15 minutes on a Holiday Monday morning (they had a chalk board for you to write your name and party size on). We got the shrimp and grits and the andouille & cheese omelette. Both were outstanding and extremely tasty. Portion size on the omelette was large, so come hungry. Grits were definitely the best I've had. Definitely stop by this place if you like southern food.

3.5/5. After dropping off my visa application at the Chinese consulate, I had a few hours to spend in the area before pick up. I somehow ended up in the Tenderloin and walked right by Brenda's. Given all that I'd heard about this place, I just had to stop by. Fortunately, as this was breakfast on a Monday morning, I only waited for a few minutes to be seats. Crawfish beignets were just as good as other reviewers have noted -- bursting with flavor and perfectly textured -- but also much bigger than I thought they would be. I was expecting puffs the size of a Porto's potato ball, so when my waiter dropped off three fist-sized crawfish-brimming balls of dough, my first reaction was that I wouldn't be able to finish them. Unfortunately (or perhaps, fortunately?), the Hangtown Fry wasn't so hot, so I left most of it, and ended up finishing the delicious crawfish beignets. The menu describes it as a crispy oyster, bacon and scallion scramble, but what I got was just bland: a thick, watery omelette with soggy oysters. I actually felt a bit sick stuffing it down my throat. Beignets were good, but I doubt I'll be back, unless I find myself in the Tenderloin on a weekday morning. The food just isn't worth waiting for.

Went here a couple months ago for the first time with a group of friends and the food was amazing! The neighborhood is a little sketchy towards one side but after we put our name in on their big chalkboard, my friends and I decided to walk a couple blocks down (in the other direction) to this Asian museum which had free entry on Sundays. We walked around inside for like 30 minutes and when we got back, our name was already called... oops! But they still took us pretty quick after that. The atmosphere is unique and fun. You can honestly just spend an hour looking at their decor. We decided to each get our own meal and order the Beignet flight for an "appetizer". My absolute favorite was the original! I'm not a seafood fan but my friends loved the crawfish, the chocolate and granny apple were pretty good but the original was just amazing! I also ordered the Croque Monsieur (weekend brunch menu) and it reminded me of the Croque Monsieur I got when I studied abroad in France... yeah it was that good. We all ordered the watermelon ice tea because it sounded amazing, it wasn't my favorite (I do like my tea pretty sweet) but it was still really good. Also, as funny as it sounds, you definitely need to try their jam! Order a side of bread just to try it... It's so fresh and yummy. They sell it separate in a jar to go too. Our server was very friendly and quick. The other staff as a whole were all very friendly even though they were super busy. One thing to note is that they do not really allow substitutions or modifications due to their heavy order load. So if you are picky, order simple. It is a very small location so it is harder to get a larger group in there. Overall, we had a great experience and we will definitely be back!

My review is for their brunch/breakfast menu and service. TL;DR - the food was surprisingly filling, awesome, delicious; and the service was great! A friend of mine from New Zealand was visiting the city and I figured what better way to start the final day of his trip was with Brenda's on a Saturday morning. I read the reviews about it being packed after 9am so I made sure to get here at opening. Sure enough, being here early not only allowed me to snag an awesome parking spot across the street (meter that doesn't start to run until 9am), but also get in before the crowd. In fact, there were many tables open at the time. I walked in and smelled delicious. The decor is extremely enjoyable. My friend noted that he liked the use of cans and buckets as utensils, knives, and condiments trays and containers. It's a comfortable area to sit and order. Because my friend was appearing my bus (he was closer so it would have been faster for him to get there instead of me going to pick him up), I had to wait ala their house rules. I had no issue because one of the wait staff, Jamie, predicted my mind and knew I wanted coffee even though I was fairly chipper. I forget the rest of the staff names, but they were all extremely friendly and welcoming. Friend from NZ finally arrives and we sit down to a menu that basically screamed at us to order it all. Again, with the benefit of foresight, I ordered the flight of beignets, which consists of one of each of their house beignets - regular, chocolate, apple, and crawfish. Although the other three made for great desserts, the crawfish beignet was the favorite. The right seasoning on the surface, the perfect texture to the dough, crawfish to cheese as a great filling. The next trip will involve only crawfish beignets. Both of us ended up ordering Eggs Benedict with Fried Chicken. Between the two of us, we barely made it through the first eggs benedict. It was surprisingly filling. The chicken was fried very well, not dry, and glazed with the hollandaise sauce over the egg and biscuit. All perfect. All delicious. This is another one of my long reviews, but it describes what I think to be a well-planned brunch at Brenda's. I can't say the same experience can be said for anything after 9am.

This place serves flights of beignets. What more do I need to say? Everything I've ever eaten there has been delicious.

I had the shrimp and cheese grits which was delicious . The beignets were all awesome . I'm sure all the rest of the meals there are just as great and will try them when I go back. Does get crowded , so prepare to wait for a seat from 20 minutes to and hour depending on the day.

Had the Brenda's Fried Chicken (BFC) for Lunch for $12.75. You get 2 pieces of Chicken, Biscuit, Coleslaw, Shoestring Fries, and a couple of Pickled Watermelon Rinds. The fried chicken was good. The batter had a little bit of spicy heat on the backend. I got a Leg and Breast. I wish I would have asked for a Leg and Thigh as the Thigh has more flavor. The Biscuit was OK, and the Fries were mediocre. Other than the Chicken, my two most favorite things were the really tasty Coleslaw, and the surprisingly good watermelon rinds. As far as I can remember, it's the first time I ever had them, and I really liked them. Now that I know how tasty it is, I would have rather asked for more Coleslaw, and skip the fries. I don't usually comment on the service; but, today for a late lunch the restaurant was only about half full. Nevertheless, we seemed to have to flag down the server, and ask for things more than once. I'd hate to see how they handle themselves with a packed house. Additionally, the hard wall surfaces, and the overall noise level, made it hard to hear the person across from me at the small 2 person table. Again, I'd hate to think what the noise level is like when they are packed. Based on what I had for lunch, I would not go out of my way to eat there, and I certainly would not stand in line to wait; but, if I were in the neighborhood, and I could just walk in and get a table, I'd go back.

The portions here are way too big. Given the location is in the tenderloin, I actually felt horrible leaving 2/3 of my plate when the second you walk out, you see starving meth heads begging for their life. the beignets were Ok. Also too big. Any time you mix dough, butter, and fry it with a delicious flavor or add-in, you will get some thing great. These were not so good that they made me want to finish the huge portions (we got the flight. couldn't finish half of it. We didn't take it back since re-heated up beignets are a horrible idea). I got the fried chicken benedict. As soon as they brought it out, I knew I could pretty much only eat the fried chicken or I would never finish. Fried chicken was ok. I was hoping it would be more crispy and crunchy like the buttermilk one at foreign cinema. Instead, the crispy layer was relatively thin and unimpressive. Make sure you're hungry if you come here. The guys at the table next to us didn't even finish their meals. I love southern/cajun food. but not sure if this place is worth the wait, especially given the neighborhood. I my be back eventually for the dungeness crab sandwich, but likely only if I am available at a random time. And maybe interesting to check out their "breakfast for dinner". Libby Jane coffee shop next door helps a bit with the wait - duck in their for coffee or something to munch on=]

My birthday fell on a weekday and I had the day off. What better way to start my day with a fabulous brunch here. Got here at 11:45 and beat the lunch crowd! Score for me! Started off with a Guava Mimosa and the BF had a Bloody Mary which we both agreed, was the best we ever had. I had a cup of the Chicken Etoufee and that was so good. Perfect mound of rice on top. Soft pillowy pieces of chicken in the most amazing sauce. Magnifique! BF had the braised short-rib with grits with comes with a side of biscuit (smear some of their home-made jam on the biscuit! DO IT. DO IT.) Luckily he was in the sharing mood. He better! It was my birthday! Because it was freaking fabulous. The grits was not like I'd ever imagine. It was creamy and DELICIOUS!! I can see how the French side came through. The braised short rib was of course fabulous with the grits. HOWEVER. The crayfish beignet was a fail for both of us. I guess we both don't like crayfish too much but when in Rome! Well, when in Rome, we failed. Sadly that was the only savory option. Service was excellent. Ambiance is great. They have high ceiling and great natural light coming through from their sky light. Fabulous all in all.

After a Friday night out we were told by locals we must try Brenda's. On Saturday morning we went to indulge on the highly spoken breakfast options.     3.5/5. After dropping off my visa application at the Chinese consulate, I had a few hours to spend in the area before pick up. I somehow ended up in the Tenderloin and walked right by Brenda's. Given all that I'd heard about this place, I just had to stop by.

    Fortunately, as this was breakfast on a Monday morning, I only waited for a few minutes to be seats. Crawfish beignets were just as good as other reviewers have noted -- bursting with flavor and perfectly textured -- but also much bigger than I thought they would be. I was expecting puffs the size of a Porto's potato ball, so when my waiter dropped off three fist-sized crawfish-brimming balls of dough, my first reaction was that I wouldn't be able to finish them.

    Unfortunately (or perhaps, fortunately?), the Hangtown Fry wasn't so hot, so I left most of it, and ended up finishing the delicious crawfish beignets. The menu describes it as a crispy oyster, bacon and scallion scramble, but what I got was just bland: a  thick, watery omelette with soggy oysters. I actually felt a bit sick stuffing it down my throat.

    Beignets were good, but I doubt I'll be back, unless I find myself in the Tenderloin on a weekday morning. The food just isn't worth waiting for.

    Went here a couple months ago for the first time with a group of friends and the food was amazing!
    The neighborhood is a little sketchy towards one side but after we put our name in on their big chalkboard, my friends and I decided to walk a couple blocks down (in the other direction) to this Asian museum which had free entry on Sundays. We walked around inside for like 30 minutes and when we got back, our name was already called... oops! But they still took us pretty quick after that. The atmosphere is unique and fun. You can honestly just spend an hour looking at their decor.

    We decided to each get our own meal and order the Beignet flight for an "appetizer". My absolute favorite was the original! I'm not a seafood fan but my friends loved the crawfish, the chocolate and granny apple were pretty good but the original was just amazing!
    I also ordered the Croque Monsieur (weekend brunch menu) and it reminded me of the Croque Monsieur  I got when I studied abroad in France... yeah it was that good.
    We all ordered the watermelon ice tea because it sounded amazing, it wasn't my favorite (I do like my tea pretty sweet) but it was still really good. Also, as funny as it sounds, you definitely need to try their jam! Order a side of bread just to try it... It's so fresh and yummy. They sell it separate in a jar to go too.

    Our server was very friendly and quick. The other staff as a whole were all very friendly even though they were super busy.
    One thing to note is that they do not really allow substitutions or modifications due to their heavy order load. So if you are picky, order simple. It is a very small location so it is harder to get a larger group in there.

    Overall, we had a great experience and we will definitely be back!

    4/13/2016

    Had the Brenda's Fried Chicken (BFC) for Lunch for $12.75.

    You get 2 pieces of Chicken, Biscuit, Coleslaw, Shoestring Fries, and a couple of Pickled Watermelon Rinds.

    The fried chicken was good.  The batter had a little bit of spicy heat on the backend.  I got a Leg and Breast.  I wish I would have asked for a Leg and Thigh as the Thigh has more flavor.

    The Biscuit was OK, and the Fries were mediocre.

    Other than the Chicken, my two most favorite things were the really tasty Coleslaw, and the surprisingly good watermelon rinds.  As far as I can remember, it's the first time I ever had them, and I really liked them.  Now that I know how tasty it is, I would have rather asked for more Coleslaw, and skip the fries.

    I don't usually comment on the service; but, today for a late lunch the restaurant was only about half full.  Nevertheless, we seemed to have to flag down the server, and ask for things more than once.  I'd hate to see how they handle themselves with a packed house.

    Additionally, the hard wall surfaces, and the overall noise level, made it hard to hear the person across from me at the small 2 person table.  Again, I'd hate to think what the noise level is like when they are packed.

    Based on what I had for lunch, I would not go out of my way to eat there, and I certainly would not stand in line to wait; but, if I were in the neighborhood, and I could just walk in and get a table, I'd go back.

    The portions here are way too big. Given the location is in the tenderloin, I actually felt horrible leaving 2/3 of my plate when the second you walk out, you see starving meth heads begging for their life.

    the beignets were Ok. Also too big. Any time you mix dough, butter, and fry it with a delicious flavor or add-in, you will get some thing great. These were not so good that they made me want to finish the huge portions (we got the flight. couldn't finish half of it. We didn't take it back since re-heated up beignets are a horrible idea).

    I got the fried chicken benedict. As soon as they brought it out, I knew I could pretty much only eat the fried chicken or I would never finish.  Fried chicken was ok. I was hoping it would be more crispy and crunchy like the buttermilk one at foreign cinema. Instead, the crispy layer was relatively thin and unimpressive.

    Make sure you're hungry if you come here. The guys at the table next to us didn't even finish their meals.

    I love southern/cajun food. but not sure if this place is worth the wait, especially given the neighborhood.  I my be back eventually for the dungeness crab sandwich, but likely only if I am available at a random time.  And maybe interesting to check out their "breakfast for dinner".  Libby Jane coffee shop next door helps a bit with the wait - duck in their for coffee or something to munch on=]

DO IT.)  Luckily he was in the sharing mood.  He better!  It was my birthday!  Because it was freaking fabulous.  The grits was not like I'd ever imagine.  It was creamy and DELICIOUS!!  I can see how the French side came through.  The braised short rib was of course fabulous with the grits.  

    HOWEVER.

    The crayfish beignet was a fail for both of us.  I guess we both don't like crayfish too much but when in Rome!  Well, when in Rome, we failed.  Sadly that was the only savory option.  

    Service was excellent.  Ambiance is great.  They have high ceiling and great natural light coming through from their sky light.  

    Fabulous all in all.
